-- 
Germany Daybook: Hochtief Cuts Earnings Target, CEO to Retire

-- B y   N i k l a s   M a g n u s s o n
-- 
2011-04-11T06:18:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-11/germany-daybook-hochtief-cuts-earnings-target-ceo-to-retire.html
Hochtief (HOT GR) cut its forecast
for 2011 earnings after its unit Leighton Holdings Ltd. said it
expected to report a loss for the financial year.  Full-year profit before tax will be half of last year’s
pretax, the company said in a statement distributed by the DGAP
newswire. In a separate statement, the builder announced that
Herbert Luetkestratkoetter will retire as chief executive
officer effective May 12, the company said in an e-mailed
statement.  EQUITIES:
*NYSE Euronext (NYX US) affirmed its $9.67 billion agreement
with Frankfurt-based Deutsche Boerse (DB1 GR), saying it will
create more value and has greater odds of winning regulatory
approval, according to a statement released after a meeting in
New York.
*Siemens (SIE GY) sold its 34 percent stake in the Areva NP
nuclear-power joint venture to  France ’s Areva (CEI FP), a
spokesman for Siemens said. Die Welt newspaper earlier reported
that Siemens sold its holding in the joint venture to Areva for
1.62 billion euros.
*Roth & Rau (R8R GR) said it “welcomes” a takeover offer to
all shareholders from Meyer Burger Technology (MBTN SW) at 22
euros a share. The company also said it signed a business
combination agreement with Meyer Burger.
*MAN SE (MAN GR) is planning to open a factory in St.
Petersburg,  Russia , the Financial Times reported, citing two
people close to the situation.
* Daimler (DAI)   is “optimistic” its joint offer for German
engine manufacturer Tognum (TGM GR) will be accepted by enough
shareholders and doesn’t plan to increase its offer, Die Welt
reported, citing Chief Financial Officer Bodo Uebber.
*Deutsche Bank’s (DBK GY) Chief Executive Officer Josef Ackermann will leave the lender when his contract expires in May
2013 and said his replacement doesn’t have to be a person from
within the company or have long-standing banking experience,
Welt am Sonntag reported, citing an interview with Ackermann.
*Hannover Re (HNR1 GY) may cut its full-year profit forecast
following the earthquake and tsunami in  Japan , Frankfurter
Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung reported, citing an interview with
Chief Financial Officer Roland Vogel.
*Hypo Real Estate (HRX GY) is likely to have a billion-euro loss
when it reports earnings, Der Spiegel reported, citing comments
made by Christian Bluhm, head of the FMS Wertmanagement unit, to
 Germany ’s parliamentary financial committee.
*Merck KGaA (MRK GY) wants to cut jobs, mainly at its Merck
Serono unit in Switzerland, to lower expenses, Financial Times
Deutschland reported, citing unidentified people with knowledge
of the plans. Merck Serono employs about 17,000 people, it said.
*Metro (MEO GY) said it is “confident” that a court ruling on
a lawsuit filed by one of the minority shareholders in its
Media-Saturn unit will be in its favor.
*MTU Aero (MTX GY) has as much as 1.5 billion euros ($2.2
billion) to spend on acquisitions if the right opportunities
arise, Boersen-Zeitung reported, citing an interview with MTU’s
Chief Financial Officer Reiner Winkler.  ECONOMY/GOVERNMENT:
*Bundesbank President and European Central Bank Governing
Council member Axel Weber said funds received by German lenders
from regional state owners will be counted as core capital in
the European Union’s stress tests.
*International Monetary Fund Managing Director  Dominique Strauss-Kahn  said there are “still unsolved problems” in
Germany’s banking industry, Financial Times Deutschland
reported.
*German Economy Minister  Rainer Bruederle  will increase his 2011
forecast for economic growth in the country this year to at
least 2.5 percent on April 14 as industrial orders rose, Focus
reported, citing unidentified people close to the government.
*German Health Minister Philipp Roesler, who’s running to become
leader of the Free Democratic Party, said fiscal consolidation
is more important than tax cuts, Frankfurter Allgemeine
Sonntagszeitung reported.
*German Finance Minister Wolfgang Schaeuble said it is unclear
whether  Greece  will need another cut in its bailout rate or a
further extension of repayment terms to return to fiscal health.
*Germany is preparing to expel the Libyan ambassador to Berlin,
Jamal Ali Omar El-Baraq, Focus magazine reported.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*European Central Bank Governing Council member Axel Weber
speaks on “The Role of Economic Policy after the Crisis” in
Bochum, Germany, at 5.30 p.m. German time.  MARKETS:
*The DAX Index rose 0.5 percent at 7,217.02
*The Stoxx Europe 600 Index rose 0.3 percent to 281.68.
*The MSCI Asia-Pacific Index was little changed at 136.52 as of
7:44 a.m. in  Frankfurt .
*German 10-year bond yield at 3.480%.
*Euro -- U.S. $1.446.  To contact the reporter on this story:
